{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff: collectors -> aggregation payload -> summary input. A unit test of one formatter would miss missing/overwritten source sections caused by wiring. Real OS/network/subprocess are not required because source clients can be in-process fakes returning deterministic payloads. Higher levels were rejected because the behavior text is about \"content passed\" (interface contract), not real infrastructure behavior or model output quality.","test_description":"Wire real collection/orchestration modules with three fake source adapters (metrics, issues, deployments). Execute one report build and assert the exact summary-input object contains fields from all three sources, with source attribution preserved.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is cross-module resilience logic (error from one source propagates into report composition) and is not a single-function concern. In-process fakes can reproduce the failure by throwing timeout/connection exceptions; no real network/OS primitive is required to validate fallback behavior. Higher levels were rejected because behavior text requires graceful degradation output, not real transport semantics or LLM judgment.","test_description":"Run orchestrator with two successful fake sources and one fake source that raises an availability error. Assert process completes, report contains a `data unavailable` marker for the failed section, and other sections are still populated.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on model output quality (faithfulness to key values), which a stubbed summarizer would always fake-pass and hide real hallucination/omission failures. This is a single model decision, not a multi-agent chain. Higher level Workflow was rejected because the behavior text targets one summary-generation decision, not multiple agentic stages in sequence.","test_description":"Provide fixed datasets with known key values and run the real summary-generation model. Score output for factual inclusion/consistency against required facts (e.g., all critical metrics/issues/deploy counts present and not contradicted) across repeated runs with acceptance thresholds.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary includes real external/API delivery and inbox reception, which mocks can hide (SMTP/API auth, TLS, provider acceptance, mailbox routing). This requires real HTTP/SMTP and process-level execution of the script. Higher level Agentic was considered, but rejected because the behavior text asserts end-to-end delivery to inbox, not model decision quality.","test_description":"Execute the scheduled script in a production-like environment against real source endpoints (or staging equivalents) and a real test mailbox. Verify one end-to-end run results in an email delivered to the configured recipient with expected subject/body structure and attached/embedded report content.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.84,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior spans real failure mode (delivery service unreachable), filesystem persistence, and cross-run retry semantics. Mocks can miss process-boundary/state persistence issues that appear only when one run writes fallback state and a later run replays it. Higher level Agentic/Workflow was rejected because behavior text is delivery fallback and retry orchestration, not LLM output correctness.","test_description":"Run 1: execute script with email endpoint intentionally unreachable; assert report file is written to configured local path with retry metadata. Run 2 (separate process invocation simulating next schedule): restore email service and assert previously saved report is retried and delivered, then fallback state is cleared/marked sent.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
